  <h1>How Much Should I Feed My Senior Dog?</h1>

  <p class="meta" style="color: var(--color-text-light); margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
    Last updated: June 2026 · 10 min read
  </p>

  <p>"How much do I feed my old dog?" is one of the most-asked — and worst-answered — questions in dog nutrition. The bag's feeding chart is built for a generic adult, and an ageing dog isn't that. Our <a href="/senior-dog-food-cost-value-uk/">senior cost-vs-value guide</a> showed <em>why</em> older dogs eat less and what that means for your budget; this page answers the practical question underneath it: <strong>exactly how much food is the right amount, and how do you work it out for your dog?</strong></p>

  <p>No product rankings here — for our actual picks see the <a href="/best-senior-dog-food-uk/">best senior dog food</a> roundup. This is the portion-and-calorie maths, in plain English.</p>

  <p><em>A note up front: these are representative figures to illustrate the method, not a substitute for veterinary advice. Every dog differs, and any sudden change in appetite or weight is a vet visit, not a portion tweak.</em></p>

  <h2>Start With Calories, Not Cups</h2>

  <p>The single biggest mistake owners make is feeding by volume — "two scoops" — when what actually matters is <strong>calories</strong>. A scoop of one food can hold twice the energy of a scoop of another, and an old dog's needs are lower than the bag assumes. So we start from calories and convert to grams at the end.</p>

  <p>There's a simple, vet-used way to estimate a dog's daily energy need in two steps:</p>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>Resting Energy Requirement (RER)</strong> — the calories a dog burns just existing: <code>RER = 70 × (bodyweight in kg)<sup>0.75</sup></code>.</li>
    <li><strong>Maintenance Energy Requirement (MER)</strong> — RER multiplied by an <em>activity factor</em>. For a typical neutered, less-active senior that factor is about <strong>1.2–1.4</strong> (a sprightly older dog sits higher; a very sedentary or overweight-prone one lower, around 1.0–1.2).</li>
  </ol>

  <p>That activity factor is where age does its work. A young, entire, active adult might be fed at 1.6–1.8 × RER; the same dog as a steadier senior drops toward 1.2–1.4. <strong>Same dog, same formula — the multiplier shrinks, and the bowl shrinks with it.</strong></p>

  <h2>Senior Calorie & Portion Table (June 2026, UK)</h2>

  <p>Here's the maths done for you. The calorie column is RER × 1.2–1.4 (a typical senior maintenance band). The grams column converts the <em>midpoint</em> of that band into a daily weight of a representative <strong>365 kcal/100g grain-free kibble</strong> — always check your own food's label, since energy density varies.</p>

  <div class="comparison-table-wrapper"><table class="comparison-table">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Senior dog weight</th>
        <th>Resting need (RER)</th>
        <th>Daily calories (senior, ×1.2–1.4)</th>
        <th>≈ Kibble per day<br><span style="font-weight:normal;font-size:0.85em;">(365 kcal/100g)</span></th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><strong>5 kg</strong> <span style="color:var(--color-text-light);font-size:0.85em;">(e.g. small terrier)</span></td><td>~234 kcal</td><td>~280–330 kcal</td><td>~80 g</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>10 kg</strong> <span style="color:var(--color-text-light);font-size:0.85em;">(e.g. small spaniel)</span></td><td>~394 kcal</td><td>~470–550 kcal</td><td>~140 g</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>15 kg</strong> <span style="color:var(--color-text-light);font-size:0.85em;">(e.g. Cocker, small Lurcher)</span></td><td>~533 kcal</td><td>~640–745 kcal</td><td>~185 g</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>20 kg</strong> <span style="color:var(--color-text-light);font-size:0.85em;">(e.g. Border Collie)</span></td><td>~662 kcal</td><td>~795–925 kcal</td><td>~235 g</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>30 kg</strong> <span style="color:var(--color-text-light);font-size:0.85em;">(e.g. Labrador, Golden)</span></td><td>~897 kcal</td><td>~1,075–1,255 kcal</td><td>~320 g</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>40 kg</strong> <span style="color:var(--color-text-light);font-size:0.85em;">(e.g. GSD, large Lab)</span></td><td>~1,113 kcal</td><td>~1,335–1,560 kcal</td><td>~395 g</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  </div>

  <p>Two things to notice. First, the calorie need climbs <em>slower</em> than weight — a 40kg dog isn't eight times a 5kg dog's portion, because the <code>^0.75</code> exponent reflects how metabolism scales. Second, these are <strong>starting points to test, not commandments</strong>. Feed at this level for 2–3 weeks, then adjust up or down based on your dog's actual body condition (see below).</p>

  <h2>Turning Calories Into Grams of Any Food</h2>

  <p>The table assumes kibble, but the conversion works for anything once you find the food's energy density on the label (metabolisable energy, usually <em>kcal per 100g</em>):</p>

  <p style="background:var(--color-bg-alt,#f6f6f6);padding:0.75rem 1rem;border-radius:6px;"><strong>Grams per day = (daily calories ÷ kcal per 100g) × 100</strong></p>

  <p>So the same 15kg senior needing ~675 kcal/day eats:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Kibble</strong> at 365 kcal/100g → ~185 g/day (cupboard-stable, calorie-dense).</li>
    <li><strong>Wet food</strong> at ~95 kcal/100g → ~710 g/day — far more <em>weight</em> of food for the same energy, because it's ~75% water. That's why <a href="/best-grain-free-wet-dog-food-uk/">wet food</a> looks like "more" in the bowl.</li>
    <li><strong>Fresh-cooked</strong> at ~140 kcal/100g → ~480 g/day, typically pre-portioned to your dog's calorie need by the subscription.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>This is also why <strong>mixing foods needs care</strong>: a topper isn't free calories. If you add wet or fresh on top of kibble, take an equal share of calories <em>out</em> of the kibble — our <a href="/food-topper-without-overfeeding/">topper-without-overfeeding guide</a> walks through the exact displacement maths, which matters most for seniors whose total need is already low.</p>

  <h2>The Real Test: Body Condition, Not the Bag</h2>

  <p>Every number above is a hypothesis to check against your actual dog. The gold standard is <strong>body condition scoring</strong>, and it takes ten seconds:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Ribs:</strong> you should feel them easily with light pressure, like the back of your hand — but not <em>see</em> them on a short-coated dog.</li>
    <li><strong>Waist (from above):</strong> a clear hourglass tuck behind the ribcage.</li>
    <li><strong>Belly (from the side):</strong> an upward tuck from chest to hindquarters, not a level or sagging line.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>If the ribs are disappearing under a pad of fat and the waist is gone, cut the daily amount ~10% and recheck in a fortnight. If the ribs, spine and hips are sharply visible, increase it — <em>and book a vet check</em>, because unexplained weight loss in an older dog can flag dental pain, kidney disease, dental loss or other illness rather than simple under-feeding. <strong>In old age, a changing shape is information; act on the dog in front of you, not the chart on the bag.</strong></p>

  <h2>Senior-Specific Adjustments</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Split into two meals.</strong> Easier digestion, steadier energy, and gentler on a senior that gets queasy on an empty stomach. It doesn't change the daily total — only the rhythm.</li>
    <li><strong>Keep protein high, calories trimmed.</strong> Slim an old dog by cutting <em>portion</em>, never protein quality — sarcopenia (age-related muscle loss) is the enemy, and protein is the defence. (More on this in the cost-vs-value guide.)</li>
    <li><strong>Re-weigh quarterly.</strong> Senior needs drift faster than adult ones. A portion that's right at ten can be 10% too much at thirteen. Recalculate from the table when the weight or activity changes.</li>
    <li><strong>Account for treats.</strong> Treats and chews are calories too — keep them under ~10% of the daily total, and subtract them from the meal maths for a dog that's gaining.</li>
    <li><strong>Watch for the appetite trap.</strong> A senior going off its food isn't a budgeting win — it's often the cue for a warm, aromatic <a href="/best-grain-free-wet-dog-food-uk/">wet</a> or fresh topper to tempt it back, or a vet visit if it persists.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The Bottom Line</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Feed calories, not cups.</strong> Estimate need with RER (70 × kg^0.75) × a senior activity factor of ~1.2–1.4, then convert to grams using your food's label.</li>
    <li><strong>Older dogs need 10–20% fewer calories</strong> than at their adult peak — the same portion quietly fattens an ageing dog.</li>
    <li><strong>Body condition beats the bag chart.</strong> Feel for ribs, look for a waist, and adjust the portion ±10% every couple of weeks.</li>
    <li><strong>Trim portions, never protein.</strong> Protect muscle by keeping protein quality high while calories come down.</li>
    <li><strong>Sudden change = vet, not maths.</strong> A gentle taper is normal ageing; an abrupt swing in weight or appetite needs a check-up.</li>
  </ul>

